WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.639
Hey there, welcome to the Paws at Data Science Hangout. I'm Libby Herron, and this is a recording

00:00:16.639 --> 00:00:22.000
of our weekly community call that happens every Thursday at 12 p.m. U.S. Eastern Time.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:27.240
If you are not joining us live, you miss out on the amazing chat that's going on. So find

00:00:27.240 --> 00:00:30.719
the link in the description where you can add our call to your calendar and come hang

00:00:30.719 --> 00:00:36.320
out with the most supportive, friendly, and funny data community you'll ever experience.

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:42.680
Can't wait to see you there. With that, I am so excited to introduce our featured leader

00:00:42.680 --> 00:00:47.439
today. We have Brian Chase, Vice President of Baseball Systems at the Miami Marlins,

00:00:47.439 --> 00:00:53.840
and I will let him introduce himself and tell you what baseball systems means. Brian, thank

00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:58.040
you so much for being here with us today. Can you tell us a little bit about what you

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:01.080
do and how you got here and something you like to do for fun?

00:01:01.080 --> 00:01:05.879
Thanks, Libby. Thanks, Rachel, for having me. Really excited to be here on the Data

00:01:05.879 --> 00:01:11.720
Science Hangout today. I'm Brian Chase. I'm the Vice President of Baseball Systems here

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:17.360
at the Miami Marlins. I'm here at the ballpark in Miami today. There's a lot of co-workers

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:22.599
from the Marlins that are on, so just wanted to give them a special shout out too. Originally

00:01:22.599 --> 00:01:29.239
from New York City, lived in New York City my entire life until February when I moved

00:01:29.239 --> 00:01:40.959
down to Miami for this job with the Marlins. My background is in computer science and media

00:01:40.959 --> 00:01:48.120
entertainment and technology MBA from NYU Stern School of Business back in 2015. Really

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:53.959
excited to be here today. Some hobbies and things that I like to do. A lot of people

00:01:53.959 --> 00:01:58.800
are musicians. I see a lot of people with guitars and instruments in the background.

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:06.279
I am an avid guitar and bass player myself. I have five guitars at my apartment here in

00:02:06.279 --> 00:02:12.320
Miami, so that's big for me. Love sports, obviously. Really love baseball. Love the

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:21.080
Marlins. Really excited to be here. At the Marlins, as VP of Baseball Systems, I oversee

00:02:21.080 --> 00:02:29.039
software engineering and product development. I oversee data engineering, data analytics,

00:02:29.039 --> 00:02:37.880
machine learning, baseball hardware, and infrastructure. Think of my teams here at the Marlins as doing

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:44.639
a little bit of everything to help our team both get good players onto the team and help

00:02:44.639 --> 00:02:50.520
get those players better. I'm really excited to be here. The Marlins are having a really

00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:56.679
good season so far relative to expectations. We're having a lot of fun here in South Florida

00:02:56.679 --> 00:03:01.199
and really excited to take your questions. Thanks, Libby.

00:03:01.199 --> 00:03:06.199
Yeah, and something that you like to do for fun, because I know for a fact you're enjoying

00:03:06.279 --> 00:03:07.800
the Florida weather a little bit more than where you came from.

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:15.479
I'm certainly enjoying the Florida weather. Love traveling, going to Argentina and Brazil

00:03:15.479 --> 00:03:23.399
in a couple of months, so really like traveling. Big poker player. Love going and playing poker

00:03:23.399 --> 00:03:29.759
with friends. And then one of the things that we do here at the Marlins for fun during the

00:03:29.759 --> 00:03:38.360
games is one of our assistant general managers, he used to be a professional baseball player.

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:45.039
And at the first inning of all home games, he will do a daily workout. And lots of people

00:03:45.039 --> 00:03:50.759
come to the clubhouse in the weight room to do a workout with former Major League Baseball

00:03:50.759 --> 00:03:54.520
player. And so I've enjoyed doing those as well.

00:03:54.720 --> 00:04:00.759
That's awesome. Well, I wish that I could say I lived in a town that had a major league team.

00:04:00.759 --> 00:04:05.399
I don't. I live in San Antonio where we have a minor league team called the Missions.

00:04:05.399 --> 00:04:10.800
And I wanted to share a picture of our mascot, which is a puffy taco, which is right on brand

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:15.759
with San Antonio. If you have a cute mascot, please share the mascot picture with me.

00:04:15.759 --> 00:04:21.720
I love mascots. Fun fact, when I was little, I was terrified of anybody in a costume, like horrified.

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:25.440
I would never have been able to do Disney, but I loved the freaking puffy taco.

00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:31.279
I would have given anything to be the kid chasing down the puffy taco at, you know, between innings.

00:04:31.279 --> 00:04:35.959
We have Billy the Marlin here at the ballpark at Lone Depot Park.

00:04:35.959 --> 00:04:41.079
Everyone seems to love Billy the Marlin. And then we also have something called the Rooster Race.

00:04:41.079 --> 00:04:51.399
During games in the sixth inning, a bunch of, I think, our interns in costumes run around and do a fake race for the fans.

00:04:51.399 --> 00:05:00.320
Well, I yeah, I love it. If anybody has adorable mascot pictures, please put them in the chat for me so that I can see them.

00:05:00.320 --> 00:05:06.320
But Brian, I wanted to ask you a couple of things about your background because you said you came from computer science.

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:10.679
I think I remember you saying that you went into finance, though, not sports,

00:05:10.679 --> 00:05:17.519
even though you were a sports kid and loved sports and like played some college basketball, maybe.

00:05:17.519 --> 00:05:29.079
So, yeah, I played a year of college basketball. I went to a Division 3 tech school called Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in upstate New York, outside of Albany.

00:05:29.079 --> 00:05:35.200
You may have heard of that. If you did, say hi in the chat.

00:05:35.200 --> 00:05:42.440
For me, coming out of school, I had done an internship at IBM.

00:05:42.440 --> 00:05:55.799
I lived in North Carolina for a year and was just like everyone, just trying to break into the industry, trying to get my first job, trying to pay off my student loans.

00:05:55.799 --> 00:06:05.119
There was a company that had a lot of alumni from RPI where they did a lot of recruiting on campus.

00:06:05.119 --> 00:06:08.760
They were called Faxet. They're still a very big company.

00:06:08.760 --> 00:06:16.239
And I got my start there as an entry level data engineer way back when.

00:06:16.239 --> 00:06:29.839
I won't age myself too much, but I spent 13 years in finance where I did a lot of database engineering, data development.

00:06:29.839 --> 00:06:32.799
Eventually, that was the early days of cloud computing.

00:06:32.799 --> 00:06:42.799
So we did a lot of client services and Google Cloud and AWS and Microsoft Azure.

00:06:42.799 --> 00:06:47.239
And that's where I got my start. But I always wanted to get into sports.

00:06:47.239 --> 00:06:55.679
And eventually, as I mentioned, I went back to school for my MBA, which I went to NYU Business School.

00:06:55.679 --> 00:07:08.640
I got my MBA in essentially sports management and sports information and looked to parlay that into a job in sports.

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:13.279
But it took a little bit of time. I eventually spent 13 years at Faxet.

00:07:13.279 --> 00:07:29.279
But in 2019, I joined the MLB League office as a principal engineer in test for MLB, in which I worked on really cool baseball infrastructure.

00:07:29.279 --> 00:07:33.600
And that's how I got my start in sports and was happy to be there.

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:37.119
I worked on the StatCast platform.

00:07:37.119 --> 00:07:45.119
If you're an MLB fan, when you watch MLB games, it says StatCast powered by Google Cloud.

00:07:45.119 --> 00:07:50.959
That's that's what I worked on when I was at MLB and worked on a lot of really fun things.

00:07:50.959 --> 00:07:56.399
Spent three seasons at the league office in New York.

00:07:56.399 --> 00:08:01.760
And then COVID happened and there wasn't really baseball for a little bit.

00:08:01.760 --> 00:08:10.559
If everyone remembers, I eventually got a job working in sports betting.

00:08:10.559 --> 00:08:19.640
I was at FanDuel for around four years where I led the technology groups for brick and mortar sports betting.

00:08:19.640 --> 00:08:33.559
So if you've ever gone to Las Vegas and gone to the sports book, then on sports, we had a number of those venues that were FanDuel owned and operated across the U.S.

00:08:33.559 --> 00:08:36.119
And eventually worked on that for a while.

00:08:36.119 --> 00:08:41.159
And now I'm back in baseball again with the Marlins here in Miami.

00:08:41.159 --> 00:08:45.200
That's kind of my journey over the last two decades.

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:49.280
Nice. I see in the chat, Craig says he used to do stats with the 76ers.

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:51.119
That's a cool fact.

00:08:51.119 --> 00:09:02.719
I wanted to talk a little bit before we hop into questions about your sort of journey into getting into the MLB job, because it took you at least like four years.

00:09:02.719 --> 00:09:05.679
Right. And there are a lot of people who are like, I'm trying to get into this.

00:09:05.679 --> 00:09:06.880
I'm trying to move into data.

00:09:06.880 --> 00:09:16.000
I'm trying to, you know, switch careers or pivot industries and are disheartened at how long it takes.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:26.159
I was wondering if you could talk a little bit about what you did in that four years and how you sort of networked and got your foot in the door.

00:09:26.159 --> 00:09:36.400
So, yeah, I knew I always wanted to get into sports and I felt like going back to school for a business degree was helping in my personal journey and development.

00:09:36.400 --> 00:09:42.000
But back in those days, there weren't a lot of avenues to get into sports at all.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.239
There weren't job boards.

00:09:44.239 --> 00:09:53.840
And so one of the things that I tried to do was go to conferences around the U.S. that focused on sports and sports analytics.

00:09:53.840 --> 00:09:58.239
Many of you maybe have heard about the MIT Sloan Sports Analytics Conference.

00:09:58.239 --> 00:10:10.080
I used to be a frequent conference goer to that conference and got the opportunity to do networking and put myself out there.

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:23.919
I was unsure if I wanted to stay in technology and sports or actually traditional front office roles in finance or marketing, accounting, those types of things.

00:10:23.919 --> 00:10:34.719
And one of the things that I had realized was a lot of these jobs are few and far between and they're very competitive.

00:10:34.719 --> 00:10:40.000
And for me, one of the things that I tried to do to help myself, kind of two things.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:53.760
One was put myself out there, did a lot of networking, cold introductions, did my own projects on the side, told people about what I was doing.

00:10:53.760 --> 00:11:09.679
And then also, it's just when you're trying to get into some of these niche industries, it's very much a apply to a lot of places and get rejected and and being able to handle rejection.

00:11:09.679 --> 00:11:17.039
If you're applying for a role and there's 500 applicants for the role, only one of 500 people get the job.

00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:29.280
So being comfortable with handling rejection, finding ways for you to stand out, whether that's in your resume, your cover letter, were all things that I did.

00:11:29.280 --> 00:11:54.559
But eventually, the way I got into MLB was through the networking at NYU and through these conferences, had friends of friends who just happened to be working at MLB, put in a really good work for me with the senior director of engineering at MLB, who reached out to me and then got an in-person interview.

00:11:54.559 --> 00:12:00.960
And when you do get those in-person opportunities, you have to take advantage of it.

00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:06.159
So you have to do a lot of preparation, a lot of mock interviewing.

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:12.640
And a lot of times these these roles are few and far between.

00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:17.840
So when you get those opportunities, you have to put your best foot forward and try to take advantage.

00:12:18.320 --> 00:12:23.760
And a lot of, and Libby, to the point, I think a lot of it can sometimes be luck.

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:27.760
And I just happened to be in the right place at the right time with my career.

00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:39.359
Same thing happened here at the Marlins, where I saw the role come up on a Monday morning, asked a former colleague if they knew anyone at the Marlins.

00:12:40.239 --> 00:12:43.359
And they happened to know someone and put in a good work for me.

00:12:43.359 --> 00:12:45.440
And the rest was history.

00:12:45.440 --> 00:12:52.640
So there's a lot of things that are in your control to put your best foot forward.

00:12:53.440 --> 00:12:58.400
But it's also a lot of luck involved and being in the right place at the right time.

00:12:58.400 --> 00:13:03.919
So I would be remiss if I said I didn't get lucky a few times in my career as well.

00:13:04.880 --> 00:13:13.039
It sounds like if anybody remembers Yerun's talk when he talked about, I think it was him, talked about surface area for luck.

00:13:13.840 --> 00:13:21.119
Or like the things that you do, the actions that you take can increase the surface area for luck to land, right?

00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:28.640
And so you had made some decisions like going back to school and going to conferences and stuff that kind of helped you out.

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:33.280
I put the Sloan Sports Conference link in the chat for anybody if they want to see it.

00:13:33.280 --> 00:13:35.359
I will make sure that that gets onto the YouTube video.

00:13:36.479 --> 00:13:40.880
But also speaking of all of this hiring talk and how to stand out and everything,

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:43.039
the Marlins are hiring.

00:13:43.039 --> 00:13:45.280
So I'm going to put that in the chat as well.

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:49.280
Feel free to ask Brian some questions about that.

00:13:49.280 --> 00:13:50.719
But hey, we're 20 minutes in.

00:13:50.719 --> 00:13:52.320
Libby, let's get to the slide of questions.

00:13:54.080 --> 00:14:01.039
So I have an anonymous question that will help us build some context around what your team does, what you work on.

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:08.400
And it is what kind of coding languages, what tools, what systems, models, etc.

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:10.960
Do you and your teams work with the most?

00:14:10.960 --> 00:14:13.119
And can you talk about some example projects?

00:14:13.119 --> 00:14:14.159
I think that's a great question.

00:14:15.520 --> 00:14:18.000
Yes, thanks for that.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:21.760
And one of the things is Libby and I were preparing for this session.

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:28.640
The Marlins have more than 40 different vendors that we work with in a technology standpoint.

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:31.359
So definitely can't go into all of them.

00:14:31.359 --> 00:14:37.200
But as I've come to the Marlins, one of the things that we've tried to do is sort of act like a

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:40.239
traditional software engineering group.

00:14:40.239 --> 00:14:46.559
So we're using standardized technologies that are used in many Fortune 500 companies.

00:14:47.280 --> 00:14:51.919
We do a lot of data and infrastructure on the cloud.

00:14:51.919 --> 00:14:54.479
Google Cloud is a huge partner for us.

00:14:55.520 --> 00:15:01.599
We're building a lot of our data engineering infrastructure using common technologies.

00:15:01.599 --> 00:15:06.400
We're building our DAGs and our ETL processes in Python.

00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:08.159
We use Airflow.

00:15:08.799 --> 00:15:13.760
We use Flyway for our database schema management.

00:15:13.760 --> 00:15:17.760
We're working in open source database tools such as Postgres.

00:15:18.799 --> 00:15:24.000
We have some Microsoft SQL Server that we have on-premises as well.

00:15:24.799 --> 00:15:28.559
And then when we're doing a lot of our software development,

00:15:28.559 --> 00:15:33.200
we're building things in React and React Native for the web and mobile.

00:15:33.200 --> 00:15:38.479
We're building traditional RESTful APIs in Python and Java Spring.

00:15:39.599 --> 00:15:44.400
And from our data science and machine learning capabilities,

00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:49.280
building a lot of R and Python models and libraries.

00:15:49.280 --> 00:15:57.280
So for me, it's a lot of traditional approaches to just problems in sports and problems in baseball.

00:15:57.840 --> 00:15:59.359
So there's a lot of overlap.

00:15:59.359 --> 00:16:06.000
And we find that it's really important to try to utilize technologies that have widespread appeal

00:16:06.559 --> 00:16:09.919
because people want to work in sports.

00:16:09.919 --> 00:16:12.719
And we love hiring good people.

00:16:12.719 --> 00:16:17.520
And one of the best ways to do that is to be working in technologies that are very approachable

00:16:17.520 --> 00:16:23.840
and are getting taught in college curriculums and things like that.

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:26.479
So yeah, very much standard.

00:16:27.359 --> 00:16:31.599
I could talk a little bit about some cool work that we're doing at the Marlins

00:16:32.559 --> 00:16:34.640
that I think would be fun for the audience.

00:16:35.440 --> 00:16:39.679
So one of the things that we have thought about,

00:16:39.679 --> 00:16:44.320
and one of our core competencies at the Marlins is just trying to be innovative

00:16:44.960 --> 00:16:49.359
and trying to think outside the box because we're competing with 29 other teams.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:51.919
And it's our goal to beat those teams.

00:16:51.919 --> 00:16:54.719
And what are the things that we can do to prepare better

00:16:55.440 --> 00:16:58.000
than our opponents to give ourselves a leg up?

00:16:58.960 --> 00:17:04.079
And we have adopted this hardware that's really cool.

00:17:04.079 --> 00:17:06.079
It's called the Traject Machine.

00:17:06.079 --> 00:17:12.079
And if you know anything about this, it's essentially a pitching simulator

00:17:12.640 --> 00:17:16.319
where the batters can take batting practice before the game.

00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:23.599
What's really cool about this technology is we get to program the Traject Machine

00:17:23.599 --> 00:17:27.520
using all the attributes for the pitchers that we're facing.

00:17:28.160 --> 00:17:32.479
And so you see their video on the Traject Machine.

00:17:33.439 --> 00:17:37.119
You see them throw just like they would throw on the mound.

00:17:37.119 --> 00:17:38.400
It's the same height.

00:17:38.400 --> 00:17:40.959
It's the same release point of the baseball.

00:17:41.760 --> 00:17:45.119
And it's the same pitches that they throw during the game.

00:17:45.839 --> 00:17:52.000
It has the exact spin rate and velocity that they normally throw at.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:57.520
So for us, it's really cool because you're able to take real life,

00:17:58.640 --> 00:18:02.479
almost simulated batting practice off the pitchers that you're about to face.

00:18:02.479 --> 00:18:07.520
So when you're starting the game, it's not like you're seeing them for the first time.

00:18:07.520 --> 00:18:10.239
It's like you're seeing them for the fourth time or the fifth time.

00:18:10.239 --> 00:18:14.319
And that's really helped us in the first inning, second inning, third inning

00:18:14.959 --> 00:18:18.239
of games where we're doing a really good job of scoring

00:18:18.239 --> 00:18:20.959
runs really early because of that preparation.

00:18:20.959 --> 00:18:24.560
So I really like nerdy baseball stuff like that.

00:18:25.119 --> 00:18:28.239
We do lots of different projects like that here at the model.

00:18:28.239 --> 00:18:29.680
That is the coolest thing.

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:33.839
I was like holding my breath the entire time you were talking so that I didn't interrupt you

00:18:33.839 --> 00:18:35.199
because I'm losing my mind.

00:18:35.199 --> 00:18:37.199
That's the coolest thing I've ever seen.

00:18:37.920 --> 00:18:45.920
This is why you need to do mock interviews when you are in a cycle of looking for a job,

00:18:45.920 --> 00:18:46.239
right?

00:18:46.239 --> 00:18:49.760
Because you don't want to be confronted with a question, an interview question,

00:18:50.560 --> 00:18:56.880
for the first time inside of that interview and be unprepared or not be in the right headspace.

00:18:56.880 --> 00:19:00.000
That's that for pitchers, for baseball.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:01.119
I think this is the coolest thing.

00:19:01.119 --> 00:19:06.000
I put a link in the chat, by the way, to the Traject Sports website.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.319
If anybody wants to go look, it's spelled funny.

00:19:08.319 --> 00:19:11.920
If you're listening to this only, it's T-R-A-J-E-K-T.

00:19:13.040 --> 00:19:14.160
Yeah, very, very cool.

00:19:14.719 --> 00:19:16.800
Well, there was another question in the chat.

00:19:18.719 --> 00:19:20.800
Not in the chat, I'm sorry, in the Slido.

00:19:20.800 --> 00:19:22.640
Everybody go ask questions in Slido.

00:19:22.640 --> 00:19:24.239
Thank you, anonymous question asker, by the way.

00:19:24.239 --> 00:19:25.119
That was a great question.

00:19:25.680 --> 00:19:30.079
That was about the hardware part.

00:19:30.079 --> 00:19:31.359
Oh, it was Morgana.

00:19:33.280 --> 00:19:34.319
We're talking about hardware.

00:19:34.319 --> 00:19:35.599
I'd love to talk a little bit more about it.

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:38.319
Morgana, are you available to ask your question live?

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:43.520
Yeah, hello, and thank you.

00:19:44.319 --> 00:19:45.599
Thanks for being here, Brian.

00:19:45.599 --> 00:19:50.880
Yeah, my question was about hardware, because I think you mentioned at the top of your talk

00:19:50.880 --> 00:19:54.800
that that was something that was looked at by your team.

00:19:55.760 --> 00:20:01.280
I was just really curious, what would data analytics have to do with baseball hardware,

00:20:01.280 --> 00:20:01.920
specifically?

00:20:01.920 --> 00:20:03.839
I'm just not familiar with that.

00:20:03.920 --> 00:20:04.420
Sure.

00:20:05.599 --> 00:20:06.959
Thanks for the question, Morgana.

00:20:09.280 --> 00:20:14.800
One of the really cool things about working in baseball is there's a lot of really fun

00:20:14.800 --> 00:20:18.000
technology and hardware in the baseball space.

00:20:18.719 --> 00:20:29.199
So one of the things that we have, I'm here at Lone Depot Park in Miami, and we have the

00:20:29.199 --> 00:20:33.599
main piece of equipment that we use is something called Hawkeye cameras.

00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:37.040
Hawkeye is a subsidiary of Sony.

00:20:37.040 --> 00:20:43.359
If you ever watch tennis and you are watching tennis and there's a replay and it's like,

00:20:43.359 --> 00:20:45.439
is this ball in or is this out?

00:20:45.439 --> 00:20:49.839
There's camera tracking that is used to track exactly where that ball goes.

00:20:49.839 --> 00:20:51.119
That's the same system.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:59.760
Here at Lone Depot Park, we have 12 cameras set up all across the concourse, essentially.

00:21:00.239 --> 00:21:07.599
And those cameras capture everything that's happening on the field from the pitcher throwing

00:21:07.599 --> 00:21:12.560
the ball to the bat, to the players on the field, even to the umpires.

00:21:13.119 --> 00:21:18.319
And so we are getting those packets of data in real time from the hardware.

00:21:19.040 --> 00:21:23.680
We are serializing that through APIs and services.

00:21:23.680 --> 00:21:29.280
And then we use all that data to do really cool analysis of what's happening on the field.

00:21:29.359 --> 00:21:37.280
So when I talk about hardware, we talk a lot about player tracking and ball tracking systems.

00:21:37.280 --> 00:21:44.800
So you may hear, there's three main companies that we work with in the space.

00:21:44.800 --> 00:21:50.800
Hawkeye, as I mentioned, Kinetrax, which is another Sony company now.

00:21:51.520 --> 00:22:00.400
They capture 300 frames per second of biomechanical data.

00:22:00.400 --> 00:22:05.280
Everything from where people are to their joint positions.

00:22:05.839 --> 00:22:08.800
And that all is XYZ coordinates.

00:22:08.800 --> 00:22:10.319
And we get all that data.

00:22:10.959 --> 00:22:16.160
We're platforming it in Snowflake and Google Cloud.

00:22:16.160 --> 00:22:19.199
And we're able to do really good analysis on that.

00:22:19.199 --> 00:22:22.319
So there's the tracking aspect of the hardware.

00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:31.680
There's just traditional infrastructure like Google Cloud and building servers and databases.

00:22:32.319 --> 00:22:33.280
Those sorts of things.

00:22:33.280 --> 00:22:39.040
But then all the other cool baseball technology that we have here at the Marlins,

00:22:39.040 --> 00:22:41.920
we're doing a lot of things with wearables.

00:22:41.920 --> 00:22:48.319
So you can have a sensor on the bat to kind of track how fast the bat is going

00:22:48.319 --> 00:22:50.800
and the angle of the bat when you're swinging.

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:56.479
Or you can wear, I don't know, a heart rate monitor or things of that nature.

00:22:56.479 --> 00:23:04.079
So there's a lot of really cool hardware that we try to use to help us get better

00:23:05.599 --> 00:23:07.040
at the game of baseball.

00:23:07.040 --> 00:23:08.239
That's really what we're after.

00:23:08.239 --> 00:23:12.880
And the more data that we have, the more inferences that we can make,

00:23:12.880 --> 00:23:16.319
the better projections that we can have on performance.

00:23:16.319 --> 00:23:20.160
And the more signal that we can have on performance, too.

00:23:20.719 --> 00:23:24.640
So all of those things combined make it really fun and exciting.

00:23:24.640 --> 00:23:25.839
Yeah.

00:23:25.839 --> 00:23:28.079
And I know I was talking with Rachel and she said that

00:23:28.079 --> 00:23:32.079
there are pregame and postgame reports that happen.

00:23:33.119 --> 00:23:38.160
So I feel like that's another aspect of the behind the scenes tools that get used.

00:23:38.160 --> 00:23:41.839
And so I was wondering how those happen and what you use for them.

00:23:43.839 --> 00:23:45.439
I think that you guys use Shiny for stuff.

00:23:45.439 --> 00:23:47.040
So I'm curious how you use Shiny.

00:23:47.040 --> 00:23:49.839
I know a lot of us here use Shiny in either R or Python.

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:52.719
But what does the reporting look like?

00:23:52.719 --> 00:23:53.439
How does that happen?

00:23:55.199 --> 00:23:55.599
Yeah.

00:23:55.599 --> 00:23:57.760
And this is where I'll give Posit the shout.

00:23:57.760 --> 00:24:00.079
We've really enjoyed working with Posit.

00:24:00.079 --> 00:24:05.040
And we're big Posit Connect users here at the Marlins.

00:24:05.040 --> 00:24:08.079
And we take advantage of the Shiny platform.

00:24:08.719 --> 00:24:14.880
And using the Shiny platform has allowed our solutions and research analysts

00:24:14.880 --> 00:24:19.040
to create really interesting reports and dashboards on top of all this data.

00:24:19.680 --> 00:24:22.160
And we use it in a few ways.

00:24:22.160 --> 00:24:25.280
One is pregame and postgame reporting.

00:24:25.280 --> 00:24:29.119
So they are creating reports on each player,

00:24:29.119 --> 00:24:33.599
the advanced materials of like the pitchers that we're facing

00:24:33.599 --> 00:24:35.520
and the batters that we're facing,

00:24:35.520 --> 00:24:41.599
as well as just instructions and guides for the players ahead of that game.

00:24:41.599 --> 00:24:47.199
And then postgame, we have similar reports to show how they did that game.

00:24:47.199 --> 00:24:49.040
Were there opportunities that we missed?

00:24:49.040 --> 00:24:51.680
Did they take advantage of those opportunities?

00:24:51.680 --> 00:24:56.079
And we're platforming all of that in Shiny apps and reports

00:24:56.640 --> 00:25:02.000
that we're able to give our coaches and players access to.

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:07.760
So Posit has really been key for us in platforming all those data

00:25:07.760 --> 00:25:09.680
and those insights in really cool ways.

00:25:10.160 --> 00:25:15.119
And my team, at the end of the day, we're not building those reports ourselves,

00:25:15.119 --> 00:25:17.760
but we are building the infrastructure and the platforms

00:25:17.760 --> 00:25:22.719
to enable other Marlins teams to do that work in easy ways.

00:25:22.719 --> 00:25:26.719
So we've abstracted away a lot of the infrastructure

00:25:26.719 --> 00:25:30.319
and the boilerplate code that they need to do to get up and running.

00:25:30.319 --> 00:25:35.520
So they can really take advantage of their core competencies,

00:25:35.520 --> 00:25:40.239
which are doing analysis and instructing coaches.

00:25:40.239 --> 00:25:42.800
And one of the key things is,

00:25:42.800 --> 00:25:48.239
how do you bring all that data and all that analytics to coaches and players

00:25:48.239 --> 00:25:52.800
and have them understand it in an easy to consume way?

00:25:52.800 --> 00:25:54.319
Because it could be overwhelming.

00:25:54.880 --> 00:25:58.880
And you always hear in baseball, there's kind of this divide of,

00:25:59.359 --> 00:26:05.359
well, the old school baseball feel versus the analytical generation.

00:26:05.359 --> 00:26:07.119
But here at the Marlins, we're doing both.

00:26:07.680 --> 00:26:13.920
And it's really important in terms of the storytelling of using visualizations,

00:26:14.800 --> 00:26:18.479
showcasing data in a way that helps tell your story,

00:26:19.119 --> 00:26:25.520
whether that's baseball or finance or business or whatever your industry is.

00:26:26.239 --> 00:26:29.439
It's one thing to have a lot of data and a lot of insights.

00:26:29.439 --> 00:26:32.800
But if you can't tell stories around that data to your audience,

00:26:32.800 --> 00:26:35.040
it's not going to have the impact that you may think it would.

00:26:35.680 --> 00:26:36.239
Right. Yeah.

00:26:36.239 --> 00:26:38.959
There's an anonymous question in Slido about this as well.

00:26:38.959 --> 00:26:42.640
It says, how do you measure ROI for the technologies that you're using?

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:46.640
And a follow on to that might be like,

00:26:46.640 --> 00:26:49.119
how do you convince people to actually use that?

00:26:49.119 --> 00:26:52.160
If you're handing coaches or players reports afterwards,

00:26:52.160 --> 00:26:53.359
how do you get them to trust it?

00:26:54.079 --> 00:26:59.040
But it sounds like your team not only handles the beginning of the pipeline

00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:01.599
where data is coming in and you're getting it organized

00:27:01.599 --> 00:27:02.800
and getting it to the right places,

00:27:03.359 --> 00:27:05.920
but also the end of the pipeline where you're actually

00:27:05.920 --> 00:27:09.119
telling those stories to decision makers.

00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:15.839
The joke that I like to make,

00:27:15.839 --> 00:27:18.959
and if you're on the Marlins and you're on this call,

00:27:18.959 --> 00:27:20.160
you probably heard this before.

00:27:20.959 --> 00:27:23.760
The baseball operations side of the Marlins,

00:27:23.760 --> 00:27:25.040
our goal is to spend money.

00:27:25.839 --> 00:27:26.880
We're just spending money.

00:27:27.439 --> 00:27:30.880
The business side of the Marlins, their goal is to make money.

00:27:30.880 --> 00:27:34.719
So the truest ROI, I think of all the work that we're doing is,

00:27:36.319 --> 00:27:39.599
are we putting a competitive team on the field?

00:27:40.479 --> 00:27:43.439
Are people coming to the games and enjoying themselves

00:27:43.439 --> 00:27:46.079
and the product that's on the field?

00:27:46.079 --> 00:27:50.000
So that's very easy, sort of holistically, right?

00:27:50.079 --> 00:27:53.839
Is, are we making more money than we're spending?

00:27:53.839 --> 00:27:55.040
Yes, we are.

00:27:56.400 --> 00:28:00.319
But two, I think another way to measure ROI is,

00:28:01.119 --> 00:28:02.800
well, are we winning more games?

00:28:02.800 --> 00:28:06.000
And there's not an exact science to this,

00:28:06.560 --> 00:28:11.599
but the Marlins ahead of the season,

00:28:12.640 --> 00:28:15.280
just coming from the sports betting background,

00:28:16.079 --> 00:28:22.000
we were projected to essentially go 62 wins and 100 losses.

00:28:23.119 --> 00:28:24.400
And that's not very good.

00:28:25.040 --> 00:28:28.400
But to date, I think someone in the chat can correct me.

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:31.599
I think our record is 54 wins and 55 losses.

00:28:31.599 --> 00:28:35.680
So we're projected to win around 78 or 79 games.

00:28:35.680 --> 00:28:38.800
So that'd be a 16 game improvement.

00:28:39.599 --> 00:28:43.680
So it's really easy to get buy-in from coaches and players

00:28:43.680 --> 00:28:48.319
when we're winning, they're seeing success on the field.

00:28:49.119 --> 00:28:51.920
Our coaching staff is doing a great job

00:28:51.920 --> 00:28:54.000
of working with players each and every day.

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:56.719
And they see the results, they're getting better.

00:28:56.719 --> 00:28:58.000
We're winning more games.

00:28:58.719 --> 00:29:01.199
So there's a lot of really good buy-in.

00:29:01.199 --> 00:29:03.280
And it starts from the top,

00:29:03.280 --> 00:29:05.920
from our president of baseball operations.

00:29:05.920 --> 00:29:08.400
He's my boss, his name is Peter Bendix.

00:29:08.400 --> 00:29:10.719
It starts from the top down in terms of the culture

00:29:10.719 --> 00:29:11.760
of what we want to set.

00:29:11.839 --> 00:29:15.439
And at the Marlins, we are using technology,

00:29:15.439 --> 00:29:18.239
we're using data, we're leaning into that.

00:29:18.239 --> 00:29:21.760
But we're not dismissing kind of the expertise

00:29:21.760 --> 00:29:24.079
of our coaching staff and our player development

00:29:25.040 --> 00:29:28.239
who has a lot of traditional baseball experience.

00:29:28.239 --> 00:29:31.680
So all in all, it's a team effort

00:29:31.680 --> 00:29:34.479
and we think we're on the right track here.

00:29:34.479 --> 00:29:36.079
Awesome.

00:29:36.079 --> 00:29:36.560
Thank you.

00:29:36.560 --> 00:29:38.640
Yeah, and somebody, I think it was Marcana

00:29:38.640 --> 00:29:39.520
mentioned in the chat, like,

00:29:39.520 --> 00:29:42.959
hey, baseball players are superstitious.

00:29:42.959 --> 00:29:44.959
I wonder if that ever plays a part

00:29:44.959 --> 00:29:46.400
in them needing to be won over.

00:29:47.280 --> 00:29:48.959
Hilarious, probably not.

00:29:48.959 --> 00:29:52.719
But thank you so much for the anonymous question.

00:29:52.719 --> 00:29:54.239
Anonymous question asked here, it was great.

00:29:54.880 --> 00:29:56.239
The ROI question.

00:29:56.239 --> 00:29:58.560
Jorge, Jorge or George has a question.

00:30:00.479 --> 00:30:03.040
Montoya, and I would love you to ask that live

00:30:03.040 --> 00:30:03.839
if you're available.

00:30:06.319 --> 00:30:08.000
Hi, yes, I'm available.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:08.880
Hey, Jorge.

00:30:09.680 --> 00:30:11.760
Yeah, so thank you for taking my question.

00:30:11.760 --> 00:30:14.000
And I'm so happy, Brian, that you're here.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:16.400
I'm from Miami, so seeing the team succeed

00:30:16.400 --> 00:30:19.040
and hear you talk all about data

00:30:19.040 --> 00:30:22.479
and the team that I like, it's really fun.

00:30:23.520 --> 00:30:26.800
So my question, I think it was partly answered already.

00:30:26.800 --> 00:30:31.520
But so I got into data very young

00:30:31.520 --> 00:30:33.680
when I watched the movie Moneyball.

00:30:33.680 --> 00:30:35.760
Probably a lot of people here too

00:30:35.760 --> 00:30:39.280
share that with the Oakland A's back in the day.

00:30:39.280 --> 00:30:41.439
But I was curious from your perspective,

00:30:41.439 --> 00:30:44.079
how has stats analytics evolved

00:30:44.079 --> 00:30:46.560
from those days to the now?

00:30:46.560 --> 00:30:47.839
I know you mentioned a little bit

00:30:47.839 --> 00:30:50.400
about like using hardware and all that.

00:30:50.400 --> 00:30:54.400
So I'm wondering what other areas

00:30:54.400 --> 00:30:58.400
is data analytics stats being used in MLB and sports?

00:30:59.839 --> 00:31:01.760
Sure, and thanks for the question.

00:31:02.239 --> 00:31:05.599
You know, obviously, for those that don't know,

00:31:05.599 --> 00:31:10.479
Moneyball was a book by Michael Lewis on the Oakland A's

00:31:10.479 --> 00:31:13.520
and how they were able to use data and analytics

00:31:13.520 --> 00:31:15.839
to field really good teams

00:31:15.839 --> 00:31:20.400
with essentially like payroll implications, right?

00:31:21.439 --> 00:31:27.199
And I think we can talk about that here too in Miami.

00:31:27.199 --> 00:31:31.359
And Miami is a pretty big metro area.

00:31:32.319 --> 00:31:35.119
We have the lowest payroll in MLB.

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:40.640
And so the question and the challenge given that

00:31:40.640 --> 00:31:46.640
is how do you maximize the development of our players

00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:52.079
on the field, given the costs, right?

00:31:52.079 --> 00:31:55.439
Like Juan Soto, if you're familiar,

00:31:55.439 --> 00:31:57.920
went to the New York Mets, signed a very huge deal.

00:31:58.239 --> 00:32:00.959
We have teams like the Yankees and the Dodgers

00:32:00.959 --> 00:32:03.680
and the Mets spending lots on payroll.

00:32:03.680 --> 00:32:07.520
And so can we get more value

00:32:08.479 --> 00:32:13.040
out of our players per dollar than other teams?

00:32:13.040 --> 00:32:14.800
And if we are able to do that,

00:32:15.439 --> 00:32:17.680
generally we're going to be successful.

00:32:18.479 --> 00:32:19.599
But to answer your question,

00:32:19.599 --> 00:32:23.280
I think the biggest change from the Moneyball era

00:32:24.239 --> 00:32:29.199
until now is there's just a lot more data

00:32:29.199 --> 00:32:33.680
that's being generated through the hardware

00:32:33.680 --> 00:32:35.280
that we had been talking about.

00:32:35.280 --> 00:32:38.880
So all the tracking technology, all the video,

00:32:40.400 --> 00:32:43.599
that wasn't there 10 years ago.

00:32:44.800 --> 00:32:47.920
You had some companies that were in that space,

00:32:49.040 --> 00:32:50.880
but MLB has done a really good job

00:32:50.959 --> 00:32:55.599
of democratizing the use of the tracking technology

00:32:55.599 --> 00:32:57.280
throughout all 30 ballparks.

00:32:57.839 --> 00:33:03.119
So there's just a lot more data than there ever was before.

00:33:03.119 --> 00:33:07.599
So a lot of data, tracking data at the major league level.

00:33:08.479 --> 00:33:11.680
We have these same systems at the minor league levels too.

00:33:12.319 --> 00:33:14.640
So if you're a minor league player for the Marlins,

00:33:14.640 --> 00:33:17.199
you're seeing the same technology footprint

00:33:17.520 --> 00:33:20.239
when you enter the minor leagues

00:33:20.239 --> 00:33:24.400
at our low A facility in Jupiter, Florida,

00:33:24.400 --> 00:33:26.959
all the way to the major leagues in Miami.

00:33:26.959 --> 00:33:29.520
So there's a consistent coaching

00:33:29.520 --> 00:33:31.280
and player development approach

00:33:31.280 --> 00:33:32.880
all the way from the minor leagues

00:33:32.880 --> 00:33:35.760
all the way up to the major leagues.

00:33:35.760 --> 00:33:38.479
So the biggest thing here is just that

00:33:38.479 --> 00:33:42.000
there's just a proliferation of more data,

00:33:43.040 --> 00:33:45.280
lots of problems in big data,

00:33:45.760 --> 00:33:48.640
but there's a lot more data being captured

00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:52.479
even for college players, for high school players,

00:33:52.479 --> 00:33:56.239
for international players that you just didn't have before.

00:33:56.239 --> 00:34:00.079
You're just used to traditional scouting approaches

00:34:00.079 --> 00:34:03.520
where people would travel all over the US

00:34:03.520 --> 00:34:06.000
and internationally looking at players

00:34:06.719 --> 00:34:11.199
and just kind of grading their talents on look and feel.

00:34:11.199 --> 00:34:13.919
But now we have data on all these players

00:34:14.879 --> 00:34:19.919
and we have models and projection systems that can be used.

00:34:19.919 --> 00:34:21.679
And I think that's the biggest change

00:34:21.679 --> 00:34:24.320
from previous Moneyball era.

00:34:24.320 --> 00:34:26.719
Yeah, do you feel like the qualitative

00:34:26.719 --> 00:34:27.360
is still in there though?

00:34:27.360 --> 00:34:29.840
Like now it's a blend of qualitative and quantitative,

00:34:29.840 --> 00:34:32.239
like is the look and feel still there from scouts?

00:34:33.760 --> 00:34:34.479
Certainly.

00:34:34.479 --> 00:34:36.639
And one of the things that we've been able to do

00:34:36.639 --> 00:34:41.679
here at the Marlins is use AI tooling

00:34:41.760 --> 00:34:43.919
to get sentiment analysis

00:34:43.919 --> 00:34:47.679
and evaluate kind of the traditional qualitative approach

00:34:47.679 --> 00:34:49.040
by our scouts.

00:34:49.040 --> 00:34:50.560
And our scouts are in the room

00:34:50.560 --> 00:34:54.159
when we are making decisions around who we draft

00:34:54.159 --> 00:34:57.840
and they're taking stands on certain players.

00:34:57.840 --> 00:35:02.399
And all of that goes into our projections and our models.

00:35:02.399 --> 00:35:05.040
So inevitably we take all those qualitative

00:35:05.040 --> 00:35:06.879
and quantitative inputs

00:35:06.879 --> 00:35:11.280
and that produces our overall Marlins sentiment

00:35:11.280 --> 00:35:12.639
on certain players.

00:35:14.320 --> 00:35:14.719
Awesome.

00:35:14.719 --> 00:35:15.919
That was a great question.

00:35:15.919 --> 00:35:17.199
Hey, thank you so much for asking.

00:35:19.120 --> 00:35:24.320
I think that, I mean, not a real question

00:35:24.320 --> 00:35:26.159
but a hilarious question in the chat.

00:35:26.159 --> 00:35:28.639
Oh, Nathan asked,

00:35:28.639 --> 00:35:31.280
and who will you be playing in the future Moneyball 2 movie?

00:35:32.239 --> 00:35:34.159
Everybody wants to see an update to Moneyball.

00:35:35.919 --> 00:35:37.040
I was gonna say Brad Pitt,

00:35:37.040 --> 00:35:39.679
but Brad Pitt's a little bit older than me now.

00:35:39.760 --> 00:35:45.040
So if you know of a good celebrity that could play me,

00:35:45.840 --> 00:35:48.000
please post in the chat.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:50.000
I'd love to hear more about that,

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:52.320
but probably my boss.

00:35:52.320 --> 00:35:55.120
My boss is the one that's gonna be portrayed in Moneyball.

00:35:55.120 --> 00:35:59.120
He is very, very good at what he does.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:03.199
He was the general manager for Tampa Bay

00:36:03.199 --> 00:36:04.639
for a number of years

00:36:04.639 --> 00:36:06.879
and they've had a lot of success at Tampa Bay.

00:36:06.879 --> 00:36:08.000
And now he's been the president

00:36:08.080 --> 00:36:09.919
of baseball operations here at the Marlins

00:36:09.919 --> 00:36:11.199
for the past two seasons.

00:36:11.199 --> 00:36:15.760
And I think he will be the one to be in the movie.

00:36:15.760 --> 00:36:16.959
Maybe I'll get a cameo.

00:36:17.600 --> 00:36:18.320
Oh, nice.

00:36:18.320 --> 00:36:19.919
Yeah, cameo would be great.

00:36:19.919 --> 00:36:20.959
We're looking forward to it.

00:36:21.919 --> 00:36:23.280
Neil had a great question.

00:36:23.280 --> 00:36:24.959
Neil always asks amazing questions

00:36:24.959 --> 00:36:25.840
and he's got an asterisk.

00:36:25.840 --> 00:36:27.199
So I'm gonna ask it for him.

00:36:27.199 --> 00:36:29.439
He says, if all teams have access

00:36:29.439 --> 00:36:31.120
to similar AI tools and data,

00:36:31.120 --> 00:36:34.399
which I assume that they all will over time eventually, right?

00:36:34.399 --> 00:36:36.639
Is there a danger that the benefits of AI

00:36:36.639 --> 00:36:38.479
will sort of plateau over time

00:36:38.479 --> 00:36:40.560
as all of these teams catch up with each other?

00:36:41.600 --> 00:36:43.520
What's your innovation process

00:36:43.520 --> 00:36:45.600
to make sure that that doesn't happen?

00:36:45.600 --> 00:36:48.080
Or are we not quite there yet?

00:36:48.639 --> 00:36:50.800
Do you feel like the Marlins are way, way ahead

00:36:50.800 --> 00:36:52.239
or are you doing some similar things

00:36:52.239 --> 00:36:54.080
to other people in the same space?

00:36:55.840 --> 00:36:56.800
I think there are things

00:36:56.800 --> 00:36:58.879
that we're doing better than other teams

00:36:58.879 --> 00:37:00.000
and things that other teams

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:01.360
are probably doing better than us.

00:37:02.239 --> 00:37:05.040
One of the things that I'm a part of at MLB

00:37:05.040 --> 00:37:08.560
is a central technology working group

00:37:09.199 --> 00:37:14.639
where MLB is democratizing certain technologies

00:37:14.639 --> 00:37:17.360
and platforms that all teams have access to

00:37:18.080 --> 00:37:19.520
because they're not necessarily

00:37:19.520 --> 00:37:22.239
competitive advantages relative.

00:37:22.239 --> 00:37:24.000
So all teams have access

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:27.840
to generally the same data and infrastructure

00:37:27.840 --> 00:37:29.600
at just like a base level.

00:37:29.600 --> 00:37:31.679
And one of the reasons why that's really important

00:37:31.679 --> 00:37:36.159
is you don't want it to be an arms race

00:37:36.159 --> 00:37:38.399
where the teams that have the most money

00:37:38.959 --> 00:37:41.600
get access to the most data and the most insights.

00:37:41.600 --> 00:37:44.080
So there needs to be some standards

00:37:44.080 --> 00:37:46.239
and governance around that.

00:37:46.800 --> 00:37:50.000
And we're happy to be part of that panel.

00:37:51.679 --> 00:37:54.879
Teams are building their own projection systems

00:37:54.879 --> 00:37:58.719
and their own models based on a lot of this data.

00:37:59.360 --> 00:38:02.320
But I think one of the differentiating factors for us

00:38:02.320 --> 00:38:03.679
and probably other teams

00:38:04.320 --> 00:38:08.320
where we can get more ingrained

00:38:08.320 --> 00:38:10.959
and more nuanced with our analytics

00:38:10.959 --> 00:38:13.199
is in the practice space actually

00:38:13.199 --> 00:38:15.120
and the non-game events.

00:38:15.760 --> 00:38:20.800
So our ability to simulate game-like conditions

00:38:20.800 --> 00:38:23.919
in practice and to track that

00:38:23.919 --> 00:38:25.919
using the same technology

00:38:25.919 --> 00:38:28.000
gets us a lot more data and insight.

00:38:29.280 --> 00:38:30.560
Than if we don't do that.

00:38:30.560 --> 00:38:33.360
So we're really investing heavily in the wearables

00:38:33.360 --> 00:38:34.080
as I mentioned,

00:38:35.199 --> 00:38:37.919
having more game-like conditions in practice.

00:38:38.719 --> 00:38:39.919
And I think at the end of the day,

00:38:40.560 --> 00:38:42.399
coaching and player development

00:38:42.399 --> 00:38:43.919
is going to be one of those things

00:38:43.919 --> 00:38:46.000
that provides the differentiation.

00:38:46.560 --> 00:38:50.800
Players buying into what we're trying to do culturally

00:38:50.800 --> 00:38:52.719
is also going to be really important

00:38:52.719 --> 00:38:55.120
because if players aren't bought in,

00:38:55.120 --> 00:38:57.520
they're not going to want to try to implement

00:38:58.159 --> 00:38:59.120
the strategies.

00:38:59.840 --> 00:39:02.320
So there's a cultural aspect.

00:39:02.320 --> 00:39:04.320
There's a practice aspect.

00:39:04.879 --> 00:39:05.600
But at the end of the day,

00:39:06.879 --> 00:39:09.679
two teams are competing on roughly the same field

00:39:09.679 --> 00:39:11.439
with the same conditions

00:39:11.439 --> 00:39:12.959
and trying to beat the other team.

00:39:12.959 --> 00:39:16.320
And we're just trying to make the best decisions that we can

00:39:16.320 --> 00:39:18.159
to put the best product in the field.

00:39:18.159 --> 00:39:21.439
But I'm not the one hitting the baseball.

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:23.520
You don't want me hitting the baseball.

00:39:23.520 --> 00:39:26.800
So people that are much better at this than me

00:39:26.879 --> 00:39:27.760
are doing that.

00:39:27.760 --> 00:39:30.879
And all that preparation,

00:39:30.879 --> 00:39:34.000
all that practice is going to be our differentiator.

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:34.879
Yeah.

00:39:34.879 --> 00:39:36.080
You know, there was a question

00:39:36.080 --> 00:39:38.159
that follows up to this really closely

00:39:38.159 --> 00:39:40.080
in the Slido from Ken.

00:39:40.080 --> 00:39:42.239
Ken, if you're available to ask that,

00:39:42.239 --> 00:39:43.280
that would be fantastic.

00:39:43.280 --> 00:39:45.120
If not, I can ask it for you.

00:39:45.120 --> 00:39:46.639
But it's on the same line.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:51.360
I'm unmuting too, Ken.

00:39:51.360 --> 00:39:51.860
Sure.

00:39:53.760 --> 00:39:54.260
Okay.

00:39:55.219 --> 00:39:56.260
Which question?

00:39:57.379 --> 00:39:59.060
So your question was about, you know,

00:39:59.780 --> 00:40:03.300
measuring all of the things that are off the field.

00:40:03.300 --> 00:40:04.739
So Brian was just saying, like,

00:40:04.739 --> 00:40:06.100
there are conditions, right,

00:40:06.100 --> 00:40:08.580
that are outside of the baseball players themselves.

00:40:08.580 --> 00:40:09.699
Your question was a little bit more

00:40:09.699 --> 00:40:10.739
about the baseball players.

00:40:10.739 --> 00:40:13.379
And I've highlighted it in Slido

00:40:14.500 --> 00:40:15.300
so everybody can see.

00:40:15.300 --> 00:40:16.659
And I'll also pop it in the chat.

00:40:16.659 --> 00:40:18.020
All right, it's at the top.

00:40:18.020 --> 00:40:18.520
Okay.

00:40:19.620 --> 00:40:21.699
My question was, yes, thank you.

00:40:21.699 --> 00:40:23.139
Are you measuring things off the field

00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:26.340
that can contribute to increased success on the field,

00:40:26.340 --> 00:40:29.300
such as sleep, weight room performance,

00:40:29.300 --> 00:40:33.459
nutrition, alcohol intake, injuries,

00:40:33.459 --> 00:40:35.300
and using those in your models at all?

00:40:36.419 --> 00:40:36.919
Thanks.

00:40:38.739 --> 00:40:42.899
What I can say is the Marlins

00:40:42.899 --> 00:40:46.419
have directors of strength and conditioning

00:40:46.419 --> 00:40:47.379
and nutrition

00:40:48.340 --> 00:40:54.260
and all sort of the non-baseball things.

00:40:54.260 --> 00:40:59.300
And we have a whole sport science team

00:40:59.300 --> 00:41:00.260
here at the Marlins

00:41:00.260 --> 00:41:03.620
that looks at everything

00:41:03.620 --> 00:41:06.340
from nutrition to sleep to medicals

00:41:06.979 --> 00:41:09.780
to everything that could affect player performance.

00:41:09.780 --> 00:41:12.820
And we try to optimize that.

00:41:12.820 --> 00:41:16.979
Even have a director of team travel here at the Marlins

00:41:16.979 --> 00:41:20.100
whose job it is to help the logistics

00:41:20.100 --> 00:41:22.500
of how we get from city to city,

00:41:23.459 --> 00:41:25.300
how we go on the airplanes,

00:41:25.300 --> 00:41:26.820
how we get to the hotels

00:41:26.820 --> 00:41:32.340
so that it's as comfortable as we can for our staff.

00:41:32.979 --> 00:41:35.379
We've invested a lot of money into nutrition

00:41:35.939 --> 00:41:37.939
here at the ball club.

00:41:37.939 --> 00:41:40.260
And having really high quality food

00:41:40.260 --> 00:41:42.979
and meals for the players is really important.

00:41:43.620 --> 00:41:49.219
And we use some of that data.

00:41:49.219 --> 00:41:51.699
I would say not a ton of it,

00:41:52.340 --> 00:41:56.100
but directionally, I think it's very easy

00:41:56.100 --> 00:41:57.780
to come to the conclusion

00:41:57.780 --> 00:41:59.459
that if you have better sleep,

00:42:00.340 --> 00:42:02.100
if you train smarter,

00:42:02.100 --> 00:42:03.139
if you eat better,

00:42:05.860 --> 00:42:06.739
all those things,

00:42:06.739 --> 00:42:09.699
you're going to have more success on the field.

00:42:10.659 --> 00:42:17.300
But that's not necessarily as predictive performance.

00:42:17.300 --> 00:42:18.739
There's a lot of variability.

00:42:18.739 --> 00:42:21.300
There's a lot of things

00:42:21.300 --> 00:42:23.139
that are just unknowns in that space.

00:42:23.139 --> 00:42:26.340
So that's probably an area of future investment too

00:42:26.340 --> 00:42:29.620
as I think about it of where can we get advantages.

00:42:29.620 --> 00:42:32.419
Yeah.

00:42:32.419 --> 00:42:34.739
If anybody is a math person

00:42:34.739 --> 00:42:36.820
or a complex systems person,

00:42:36.820 --> 00:42:38.580
any system that has a human being

00:42:38.580 --> 00:42:41.060
and it is complex into a baseball team

00:42:41.060 --> 00:42:43.860
is like a wildly complex system

00:42:43.860 --> 00:42:45.060
with so many variables.

00:42:45.699 --> 00:42:46.979
There are a couple more questions

00:42:46.979 --> 00:42:48.260
that I would love to get to.

00:42:48.260 --> 00:42:49.939
They're sort of along these lines.

00:42:51.379 --> 00:42:53.379
One of them, speaking of variables,

00:42:54.179 --> 00:42:56.739
was an anonymous question that was like,

00:42:57.459 --> 00:42:58.899
what is the thought process

00:42:58.899 --> 00:43:01.060
that goes behind developing a new feature

00:43:01.620 --> 00:43:03.459
in a data analytics or ML model

00:43:03.459 --> 00:43:05.139
in the realm of sports analytics?

00:43:06.100 --> 00:43:08.739
The development of key actionable metrics

00:43:08.739 --> 00:43:10.739
seems like a big part of the job

00:43:10.739 --> 00:43:12.659
and I'm excited to hear your talk on it.

00:43:12.659 --> 00:43:14.659
So I don't know if you have your hands

00:43:14.659 --> 00:43:17.379
in feature engineering or if your teams do.

00:43:17.379 --> 00:43:19.060
Do you have anything to talk about on that side?

00:43:20.899 --> 00:43:21.860
Yeah, one of the things

00:43:21.860 --> 00:43:24.020
that we've been really taking a look at

00:43:24.020 --> 00:43:25.939
here at the Marlins in a broad sense

00:43:25.939 --> 00:43:29.939
are what are the data points

00:43:30.979 --> 00:43:34.500
that best tell the stories about player performance?

00:43:35.300 --> 00:43:36.979
And there's all these stats, right?

00:43:36.979 --> 00:43:38.580
There's all these things that happen

00:43:38.580 --> 00:43:40.260
on the field and off the field.

00:43:41.139 --> 00:43:44.899
But eventually we build all these models

00:43:44.899 --> 00:43:46.659
and there's all these outputs,

00:43:46.659 --> 00:43:49.300
but effectively we just come

00:43:49.300 --> 00:43:52.500
to very sort of core numbers.

00:43:53.300 --> 00:43:55.540
And in baseball,

00:43:55.540 --> 00:43:58.419
it's effectively a couple of things.

00:43:59.459 --> 00:44:02.500
One, you've probably heard about this a lot.

00:44:02.500 --> 00:44:04.340
It's called wins above replacement

00:44:04.340 --> 00:44:07.300
and it's effectively MLB's calculation

00:44:07.300 --> 00:44:10.739
of how good is a player relative

00:44:10.739 --> 00:44:12.500
to just someone coming up

00:44:12.500 --> 00:44:14.100
from the minor leagues essentially.

00:44:14.899 --> 00:44:18.979
And so our ability to project that value

00:44:18.979 --> 00:44:21.540
into the future successfully

00:44:22.260 --> 00:44:23.780
gives us really good insights

00:44:23.780 --> 00:44:26.580
into how a player is going to perform.

00:44:27.939 --> 00:44:33.459
The other is a pretty widely adopted standard,

00:44:33.540 --> 00:44:34.979
but at the Marlins,

00:44:34.979 --> 00:44:37.139
we call it surplus value.

00:44:37.860 --> 00:44:43.219
And that is based on their projections

00:44:43.219 --> 00:44:47.139
and their contract and all those obligations.

00:44:47.939 --> 00:44:52.100
How much value does that player have to the team?

00:44:52.100 --> 00:44:54.260
Like just for like dollars and cents.

00:44:55.219 --> 00:45:00.020
So we just had the trade deadline last week

00:45:00.020 --> 00:45:01.860
and we made a few trades

00:45:01.860 --> 00:45:03.300
and we didn't make a few trades,

00:45:04.500 --> 00:45:06.659
but the key thing for us is,

00:45:08.179 --> 00:45:10.260
okay, if this player we think is worth,

00:45:11.620 --> 00:45:14.739
I don't know, 20 million dollars of surplus value,

00:45:14.739 --> 00:45:16.979
we essentially want to get players back

00:45:16.979 --> 00:45:22.820
that equal or surpass our surplus value calculations.

00:45:22.820 --> 00:45:24.899
And teams all calculate this differently.

00:45:24.899 --> 00:45:27.219
So there are market inefficiencies

00:45:27.219 --> 00:45:29.060
and information asymmetry

00:45:29.060 --> 00:45:33.860
that can mean that both sides can feel

00:45:33.860 --> 00:45:35.780
like they're ripping the other team off.

00:45:35.780 --> 00:45:37.379
But in actuality,

00:45:38.899 --> 00:45:41.379
both teams like the other team's players better.

00:45:42.100 --> 00:45:44.419
So there's a lot of nuance,

00:45:44.419 --> 00:45:45.780
but at the end of the day,

00:45:47.459 --> 00:45:50.580
we have come and sort of gotten consensus

00:45:50.580 --> 00:45:53.860
on what we feel the key data items are.

00:45:53.860 --> 00:45:55.620
And a lot of our R&D efforts

00:45:55.620 --> 00:45:58.419
are working towards how can we get as accurate

00:45:58.419 --> 00:46:03.459
as we can with those 10 to 20 data items.

00:46:03.459 --> 00:46:05.780
And that really guides the story for everything.

00:46:06.340 --> 00:46:08.100
And when we're building applications,

00:46:08.100 --> 00:46:11.219
it's how do we platform that data

00:46:11.219 --> 00:46:14.260
in a way that looks and feels right.

00:46:14.260 --> 00:46:17.939
And we're focusing a lot on data visualization

00:46:18.979 --> 00:46:20.020
and data design

00:46:20.739 --> 00:46:23.379
so that we can tell those stories with data really easily.

00:46:24.020 --> 00:46:26.580
And the last thing we want to do is waste time,

00:46:27.540 --> 00:46:29.699
just as an example from the trade deadline,

00:46:30.580 --> 00:46:33.699
if I feel like one player is worth $20 million

00:46:33.699 --> 00:46:36.899
and Libby thinks that player's worth $25 million

00:46:36.899 --> 00:46:39.379
and Rachel feels like that player's worth $15 million,

00:46:40.340 --> 00:46:43.379
now we're sort of going back and forth

00:46:43.379 --> 00:46:45.459
on what we think the true value of the player is

00:46:45.459 --> 00:46:48.260
rather than this is what the Marlins think

00:46:48.260 --> 00:46:49.780
this player is worth.

00:46:49.780 --> 00:46:51.379
And that's what we're going to use as the basis

00:46:51.379 --> 00:46:53.860
because we know what has gone into those calculations

00:46:54.020 --> 00:46:55.780
that we all agree in the methodology

00:46:56.419 --> 00:46:58.179
that went into those calculations.

00:46:59.060 --> 00:47:00.500
And that was really important for us.

00:47:01.139 --> 00:47:05.620
This trade deadline was having consensus

00:47:05.620 --> 00:47:08.580
on what we thought the methodology was

00:47:08.580 --> 00:47:12.820
and trusting the modeling and the analytical results

00:47:12.820 --> 00:47:14.820
and using that as our source of truth.

00:47:16.100 --> 00:47:18.260
Awesome. That was fantastic.

00:47:18.260 --> 00:47:20.179
I think that was an anonymous question.

00:47:20.179 --> 00:47:21.300
Thank you, anonymous asker,

00:47:21.300 --> 00:47:22.580
whoever you are for asking that.

00:47:24.580 --> 00:47:26.899
We only have about five minutes left,

00:47:28.500 --> 00:47:32.020
but I think that we can probably get one more in.

00:47:32.020 --> 00:47:34.659
There was one from, I think it was from Joe

00:47:35.939 --> 00:47:37.219
and I'm unable to find it.

00:47:37.860 --> 00:47:38.659
There it is.

00:47:38.659 --> 00:47:40.340
Joe, are you available to ask your question?

00:47:40.340 --> 00:47:41.540
I'm going to highlight it in Slido

00:47:41.540 --> 00:47:42.739
so it's going to go straight to the top

00:47:42.739 --> 00:47:44.020
so that you can see it.

00:47:44.020 --> 00:47:44.820
I am. Thank you.

00:47:45.300 --> 00:47:46.179
Hey, Joe.

00:47:46.179 --> 00:47:47.860
Yeah, I think I worded it like,

00:47:49.860 --> 00:47:51.459
if you're getting from a different industry,

00:47:51.459 --> 00:47:55.139
what might I be surprised by?

00:47:55.139 --> 00:47:56.580
I guess another way is like,

00:47:56.580 --> 00:47:58.659
do I really want to turn my hobby into a job

00:47:58.659 --> 00:48:00.100
and tell me why not?

00:48:02.899 --> 00:48:08.020
Well, as someone who turned a hobby into a job,

00:48:08.020 --> 00:48:09.860
I'd say it's been great so far.

00:48:09.860 --> 00:48:14.179
So yeah, I think there's that adage of like,

00:48:14.179 --> 00:48:15.620
oh, if you're doing something for fun

00:48:15.620 --> 00:48:18.899
and now you're doing something for a job,

00:48:18.899 --> 00:48:20.419
is it still going to be fun?

00:48:20.500 --> 00:48:22.260
And the idea is,

00:48:22.820 --> 00:48:26.500
well, what are the things that we can do to keep it fun?

00:48:27.300 --> 00:48:32.260
And for me, one of the things that I've tried to do is,

00:48:33.620 --> 00:48:37.620
I've taken advantage of AI actually a lot in this space

00:48:37.620 --> 00:48:40.260
using tools like ChatGPT

00:48:40.820 --> 00:48:43.060
to help me with, quote unquote,

00:48:43.060 --> 00:48:46.100
the not fun things about the job, right?

00:48:46.100 --> 00:48:50.979
Creating documentation or, I don't know,

00:48:50.979 --> 00:48:53.060
doing budgeting or random things

00:48:53.060 --> 00:48:56.020
that are just like not fun baseball stuff.

00:48:56.739 --> 00:49:00.100
And if I can get really good at harnessing the power of AI

00:49:00.100 --> 00:49:01.300
to do a lot of those things,

00:49:02.419 --> 00:49:05.620
now it gives me the opportunity to do all the fun stuff.

00:49:06.179 --> 00:49:10.179
So it allows me to travel to our minor league teams

00:49:10.179 --> 00:49:11.699
and see how they're doing

00:49:11.699 --> 00:49:15.620
or work with a vendor on some cool new tech

00:49:16.500 --> 00:49:19.300
and go downstairs into the clubhouse

00:49:19.300 --> 00:49:21.219
where indoor batting cages are

00:49:21.219 --> 00:49:23.939
and play around with the Traject machine, as I'd mentioned.

00:49:24.580 --> 00:49:29.060
So for me, I think if you're someone that has hobbies

00:49:30.260 --> 00:49:32.419
and you're like, this is really fun,

00:49:33.459 --> 00:49:35.939
I think it's better to have a job

00:49:35.939 --> 00:49:38.580
where you are trying to have fun

00:49:38.580 --> 00:49:42.020
than one that feels like a job and you dread going to.

00:49:42.100 --> 00:49:47.939
So I would certainly try to join companies and jobs

00:49:47.939 --> 00:49:50.739
where you're passionate about what the company does,

00:49:51.459 --> 00:49:53.540
you're passionate about what you'd be working on.

00:49:54.340 --> 00:49:56.419
You only have one life,

00:49:57.060 --> 00:49:58.979
so you might as well have fun doing it.

00:49:58.979 --> 00:50:02.100
And at the Marlins, I think we're doing a good job of,

00:50:03.379 --> 00:50:06.260
we have a lot of really smart, talented people.

00:50:06.260 --> 00:50:08.419
They are very passionate about what they do.

00:50:08.419 --> 00:50:10.020
They care a lot about what they do

00:50:10.020 --> 00:50:11.219
and they take it seriously.

00:50:12.260 --> 00:50:14.100
But this is baseball, it should be fun.

00:50:14.100 --> 00:50:16.419
And that's something that we try to do every day

00:50:16.419 --> 00:50:18.419
is make sure that we're having a good time.

00:50:18.419 --> 00:50:20.580
That's great advice.

00:50:20.580 --> 00:50:23.060
We usually try to get a career advice question

00:50:23.699 --> 00:50:27.219
in before the end, but I think that covers it.

00:50:27.219 --> 00:50:30.020
Yeah, there were some other career advice questions

00:50:30.020 --> 00:50:33.780
that you could rapid fire answer as quickly as you wanted to.

00:50:35.379 --> 00:50:36.739
Because Zach had asked like,

00:50:36.739 --> 00:50:40.739
hey, it took you four years to get that job in sports.

00:50:40.899 --> 00:50:43.540
Did you feel discouraged at all?

00:50:43.540 --> 00:50:46.500
Did you consider maybe I'm not going the right direction?

00:50:46.500 --> 00:50:50.260
And then also Aaron had asked, was that MBA worth it?

00:50:50.260 --> 00:50:52.739
Do you feel like you could have succeeded without it?

00:50:52.739 --> 00:50:55.939
So maybe a rapid fire answer on that one might be cool.

00:50:57.219 --> 00:50:59.780
Yeah, well, I think on the MBA front,

00:51:01.060 --> 00:51:03.060
I definitely feel like it was worth it to me,

00:51:03.860 --> 00:51:06.020
just the connections that I made,

00:51:06.020 --> 00:51:07.620
the education that I got,

00:51:08.419 --> 00:51:11.379
and the opportunities that going to a school like NYU

00:51:11.379 --> 00:51:13.459
opened up for me was worth it.

00:51:13.459 --> 00:51:14.820
Is it worth it for everyone?

00:51:15.780 --> 00:51:18.979
It's hard for me to answer that, but for me it was.

00:51:20.419 --> 00:51:23.300
So I think it's really in the eye of the beholder.

00:51:24.659 --> 00:51:26.100
Remind me of the other question, Libby?

00:51:26.820 --> 00:51:27.780
The other question was,

00:51:27.780 --> 00:51:29.540
did you ever get discouraged in that four years

00:51:29.540 --> 00:51:30.340
and think about like,

00:51:30.340 --> 00:51:32.020
oh, maybe I should go a different direction?

00:51:33.860 --> 00:51:34.580
That's a no.

00:51:34.580 --> 00:51:38.899
I think one of the things that was really in my favor

00:51:38.899 --> 00:51:41.860
is I had the luxury of working at a company in finance

00:51:41.860 --> 00:51:44.500
that I actually really liked and I liked what I was doing.

00:51:44.500 --> 00:51:48.659
So it was four years, but I had the luxury of

00:51:49.620 --> 00:51:52.100
not having to take the first thing necessarily

00:51:52.100 --> 00:51:54.419
that popped into my inbox.

00:51:54.979 --> 00:51:57.860
Not everyone has that luxury, I understand.

00:51:57.860 --> 00:52:03.540
But for me, I had very clear goals of what I wanted to do

00:52:03.540 --> 00:52:06.500
and I wasn't, you know, when I went to NLB,

00:52:07.379 --> 00:52:10.100
I sort of took a leap of faith

00:52:10.100 --> 00:52:11.939
and I was doing something that I wasn't like,

00:52:12.820 --> 00:52:15.379
I would say the most qualified to do,

00:52:15.379 --> 00:52:17.379
but it was really good to get in the door.

00:52:18.100 --> 00:52:20.260
I grinded a lot, I learned a lot,

00:52:20.260 --> 00:52:23.699
and that opened up doors and other avenues.

00:52:23.699 --> 00:52:27.139
So was I discouraged?

00:52:27.139 --> 00:52:28.340
Probably at times, right?

00:52:28.979 --> 00:52:32.979
Being rejected in anything is not necessarily fun,

00:52:32.979 --> 00:52:36.580
but you learn to have thick skin,

00:52:36.580 --> 00:52:40.580
you learn to know sort of what your worth is.

00:52:40.580 --> 00:52:43.540
And a lot of times the rejections

00:52:44.179 --> 00:52:46.340
have nothing to do with you as an individual.

00:52:46.899 --> 00:52:51.060
Maybe just, you know, luck of the draw in some cases

00:52:51.060 --> 00:52:56.260
or networking or like, there's so many variables.

00:52:56.260 --> 00:52:57.459
So one of the best-

00:52:57.459 --> 00:52:58.979
It's a numbers game sometimes.

00:52:58.979 --> 00:52:59.939
So many applications.

00:53:00.100 --> 00:53:04.020
I wouldn't take it personally.

00:53:04.020 --> 00:53:08.179
Just understand that in anything, it's a business

00:53:08.179 --> 00:53:11.139
and a lot of times these are business decisions

00:53:11.139 --> 00:53:13.060
and it's never personal.

00:53:14.020 --> 00:53:16.979
Yeah, whoever you are, you are wonderful

00:53:16.979 --> 00:53:18.820
applying for jobs and getting lots of rejections.

00:53:18.820 --> 00:53:20.100
The market's really tough right now.

